# How to use @nu-art/db-api-shared

Use this package for types and API definitions shared between db-api frontend and backend so both sides stay in sync. No runtime server or client—only types, query shapes, and CRUD API definitions.

## Dependencies

Add `@nu-art/db-api-shared`; it depends on `@nu-art/ts-common`, `@nu-art/http-client` (for ApiDef/BodyApi/QueryApi in CrudApiTypes), and `@nu-art/firebase-shared` (e.g. EntityDependencyError). Consuming packages typically also use `@nu-art/http-client` or `@nu-art/api-types` where API types are used.

## Core usage

### CrudTypes (entity contract)

- `CrudTypes<DBKey, DBItem, UIItem, Validator, UniqueKeys>`: defines the entity contract—dbKey, dbItem (full DB object), uiItem (UI/modifiable shape), validator, uniqueKeys. Use the same CrudTypes on both FE and BE.

### CrudApiDef and CrudApiTypes

- `CrudApiDef(dbKey, version?)` returns `CrudApiDef_Type<Types>`: API definitions for query, queryUnique, upsert, upsertAll, deleteUnique, deleteQuery, deleteAll (paths like `{version}/{dbKey}/query`, etc.). Use with @nu-art/http-server on BE and @nu-art/http-client on FE.
- `CrudApiTypes<Types>`: typed API shapes (BodyApi/QueryApi) for each CRUD operation. Backend and frontend use these for handler and caller types.

### Query types

- `CrudQuery<T>`, `CrudClause_Where<T>`, `CrudClause_OrderBy<T>`, `CrudClause_Select<T>`, `CrudQueryComparator`, `CrudWhereValue`: db-agnostic query shape (structurally compatible with Firestore wire format).
- `CrudEmptyQuery`: constant empty query for “delete all” style operations.

### DB and prototype types

- `DB_Object`, `DB_BaseObject`, `DB_Key`, `DBPointer` from `types/db-object.js`.
- `Database<Proto>`, `DB_Prototype`, `Proto_DB_Object`, `OmitDBObject`, `DBIndex`, `VersionsDeclaration`, `TypeOfTypeAsString`, etc.: for defining entity metadata and versioning; used by apps that define DB_Prototype entity defs. Backend base (ModuleBE_BaseDB) uses only the minimal `BaseDBDefBE` shape from db-api-backend, not Proto.

### Alternative: Database + DBDef

Entities can use the **Database + DBDef** style instead of the full CrudTypes/DB_Prototype pattern. Use **`DatabaseDef_<Entity>`** for the entity prototype type and **`DBDef_<Entity>`** or **`DBDef_<Plural>`** for the runtime constant. Implement the type as `DB_Prototype<DB_ProtoSeed<...>>`. Define a `Database<DatabaseDef_<Entity>>` constant with `dbKey`, `entityName`, `modifiablePropsValidator`, `generatedPropsValidator`, `versions`, `uniqueKeys`, `frontend`/`backend`.

**Generated keys and generatedProps:** In `DB_ProtoSeed`, `generatedKeys` must be either `never` (no entity-specific generated props) or a union of keys of the entity type `T` that are **not** in `keyof DB_Object` — i.e. only entity-specific generated props; base DB_Object keys are a given and must not be listed. On the Database constant: when the proto has generated props (generatedKeys not `never`), include `generatedProps` (required); when generatedKeys is `never`, do not include `generatedProps`. The `Database<Proto>` type enforces this via a conditional on `Proto['generatedProps']`.

Same shared types and backend/frontend steps apply: `DB_Object` from here, `createApisForDBModule` on backend, `ModuleBE_BaseDB<DatabaseDef_<Entity>>`, `ModuleFE_BaseApi<DatabaseDef_<Entity>>`.

## Convention

- Define CrudTypes and use CrudApiDef with the same dbKey and version on both frontend and backend. Shared is the single place for CRUD API shapes and query types so FE/BE stay aligned.
